[[File:Biosphere Data 2000 through 2004.ogv|thumb|300px|Animation depicting nearly four years worth of [[SeaWiFS]] ocean chlorophyll concentration.]]

'''Chlorophyll''' (also '''chlorophyl''')  is a green [[pigment]] found in [[cyanobacteria]] and the [[chloroplast]]s of [[alga]]e and [[plant]]s.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.chm.bris.ac.uk/motm/chlorophyll/chlorophyll_h.htm | title =Chlorophyll | author =Paul May | author2 =''[[University of Bristol]]'' | publisher =bris.ac.uk}}</ref> Its name is derived from the [[Greek language|Greek]] words χλωρός, ''chloros'' ("green") and φύλλον, ''phyllon'' ("leaf").<ref name=OnlineEtDict>{{cite web|title=chlorophyll|url=http://www.etymonline.com/index.php?term=chlorophyll&allowed_in_frame=0|publisher=[[Online Etymology Dictionary]]}}</ref> Chlorophyll is an extremely important biomolecule, critical in [[photosynthesis]], which allows plants to absorb [[energy]] from light. Chlorophyll absorbs light most strongly in the [[Diffuse sky radiation|blue portion]] of the [[electromagnetic spectrum]], followed by the red portion. However, it is a poor absorber of green and near-green portions of the spectrum, hence the green color of chlorophyll-containing tissues.<ref>Chlorophyll molecules are specifically arranged in and around photosystems that are embedded in the thylakoid membranes of chloroplasts.
{{cite web
| author = Speer, Brian R.
| year = 1997
| title = Photosynthetic Pigments
