}}</ref>

==Alternative medicine==
There are many claims that are made about the healing properties of chlorophyll but most have been disproved or are exaggerated by the companies that are marketing them. Claims that chlorophyll is "the blood of plants" is simply incorrect and stems from the fact that it is similar in structure to [[Heme]] which is a component of [[haemoglobin]]. Quackwatch, a website dedicated to debunking false medical claims, has a quote from Teledo Blade which claims <ref>[http://www.quackwatch.org/01QuackeryRelatedTopics/DSH/chlorophyll.html Amazing Claims for Chlorophyll], [[Quackwatch]]</ref> "Chlorophyll Held Useless As Body Deodorant"  Dec 10, 1952, <ref>"Chlorophyll Held Useless As Body Deodorant", Toledo Blade, Dec 10, 1952</ref> but later has John C. Kephart pointing out "No deodorant effect can possibly occur from the quantities of chlorophyll put in products such as gum, foot powder, cough drops, etc. To be effective, large doses must be given internally" [Journal of Ecological Botany 9:3, 1955].

